# Notes
# â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•

# 1. NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix:
#    - Variables with this prefix are bundled into client-side JavaScript
#    - Safe for non-sensitive config (Firebase config, API URLs, feature flags)
#    - Anyone can view these in browser DevTools

# 2. Server-only variables (no prefix):
#    - Never exposed to the client
#    - Use for secrets (API keys, database credentials, session secrets)
#    - Only accessible in Next.js API routes and server components

# 3. NODE_ENV:
#    - Automatically set by build tools (development, production, test)
#    - DO NOT set manually in .env files

# 4. Build-time vs Runtime:
#    - NEXT_PUBLIC_ variables are replaced at BUILD time
#    - Server-only variables are read at RUNTIME
#    - Changing NEXT_PUBLIC_ vars requires rebuild

# 5. Vercel deployment:
#    - Set environment variables in Vercel dashboard
#    - Use different values for Production, Preview, Development scopes
#    - Vercel automatically loads them into process.env

